0. Project Overview

Project#2 is all about cleaning and analyzing the data, including identifying and handling outliers, describing the shape of the data, and selecting appropriate measures of central tendency and spread. The goal of the analysis is to gain a better understanding of the distribution and characteristics of the data, and to make informed decisions about how to analyze and interpret it. To summarize, this task requires a combination of data cleaning, data visualization, and statistical analysis skills, and is designed to help the students develop a more complete and accurate understanding of the data.

Univariate analysis typically involves computing summary statistics, such as mean, median, mode, variance, standard deviation, and other measures of central tendency and variability. It may also involve creating visualizations of the data, such as histograms, box plots, and density plots, to gain insight into the distribution of the variable.

Bivariate analysis in R involves exploring the relationship between two variables. This can be done by computing the correlation coefficient between the two variables, creating a scatter plot to visualize the relationship, and fitting a regression model to the data. In addition, there are many packages in R, such as ggplot2 and lattice, that provide tools for creating more advanced visualizations of bivariate data.

# Calculate the z-score for the Order Value column
z <- abs(scale(smd$Order_Value))

# Identify the index of any z-score greater than 3 (typical threshold for identifying outliers)
outliers <- which(z > 3)

# Print the outliers

## [1] 5046

Mode

get_mode <- function(x) {
  unique_x <- unique(x)
  unique_x[which.max(tabulate(match(x, unique_x)))]
}

mode_value <- get_mode(smd$Order_Value)
print(mode_value)
## [1] 4858

6. Choose and calculate a measure of spread (SD, MAD or IQR) that is appropriate for your chosen measure of central tendency. Explain why you chose this as your measure of spread.

Since the shape of the data is uniform, all three measures of central tendency (mean, median, and mode) would be appropriate. The mean is 5051.86, the median is 5056, and the mode is 8677. In this case, the mode is quite far from the mean and median, which suggests that it may not be the most representative measure of central tendency. Since the mean and median are very close in value and the mode is significantly different, it is appropriate to use the median as the measure of central tendency to better represent the typical value in the data.

7. Choose and calculate a measure of spread (SD, MAD or IQR) that is appropriate for your chosen measure of central tendency. Explain why you chose this as your measure of spread.

Since the shape of the data is uniform,the distribution is approximately symmetric, I would choose the interquartile range (IQR) as the measure of spread.The IQR is a robust measure of spread and is less sensitive to outliers compared to the standard deviation. Additionally, since the median is used as a measure of central tendency, the IQR is a natural choice as it is based on quartiles and is also robust to outliers.

IQR is defined as the range between the 25th and 75th percentiles.In this case, the median is 5056, which is the 50th percentile. Therefore, the IQR can be calculated as the difference between the 75th and 25th percentiles, which are 7517 and 2575 respectively.

IQR = 7517 - 2575 = 4942

So, the IQR for this dataset is 4942.

meal_counts$prop <- meal_counts$count / sum(meal_counts$count)

Bivariate Analysis

PAIR I : Both variables are Numeric

1. Create an appropriate plot to visualize the relationship between two numeric variables “Meal served each year” and “Order value”

# Remove outliers in Order_Value and YYYY_Meal_Served_Year
smd_cleaned <- smd %>%
  filter(YYYY_Meal_Served_Year != 2013 & YYYY_Meal_Served_Year != 2019) %>%
  mutate(Order_Value = ifelse(Order_Value < quantile(Order_Value, 0.01) | Order_Value > quantile(Order_Value, 0.99), NA, Order_Value))

# Plot to visualize the relationship between two numeric variables
ggplot(smd_cleaned, aes(x = YYYY_Meal_Served_Year, y = Order_Value)) + 
  geom_point(color = "Brown") + 
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Sales Order", title = "Sales Order by year") +
  theme_minimal()+
   theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 18, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
        legend.position = "right", legend.justification = "center",
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        axis.line = element_line(linewidth = 1),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 10),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"))
## Warning: Removed 994 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

2. Describe the form, direction, and strength of the observed relationship.

Based on the plot of “YYYY_Meal_Served_Year” and “Order_Value”, the form of the relationship appears to be linear, meaning that the data points follow a somewhat straight line pattern.

The direction of the relationship is positive. As the year increases, the order value tends to increase as well.This means that there is a general trend of higher order values over time.

To calculate the strength of the relationship between “YYYY_Meal_Served_Year” and “Order_Value”, we can use a correlation coefficient. In this case, since both variables are numeric, we can use Pearson’s correlation coefficient. The value of the correlation coefficient ranges between -1 and 1, where -1 indicates a perfectly negative correlation, 0 indicates no correlation, and 1 indicates a perfectly positive correlation.

We can calculate the correlation coefficient between the two variables using the cor() function in R:

cor(smd$YYYY_Meal_Served_Year, smd$Order_Value)
## [1] 0.006473214

A correlation coefficient of 0.007286711 indicates a very weak positive correlation between the two variables, “YYYY_Meal_Served_Year” and “Order_Value”. This means that there is a slight tendency for order values to increase as the year increases, but the relationship is not very strong.

3. Explain what this relationship means in the context of the data.

The relationship between “YYYY_Meal_Served_Year” and “Order_Value” suggests that there is no significant variation in the average order value across different years. This means that the order value has remained relatively stable over the years, without showing any consistent trend of increase or decrease. It is possible that the prices of the meals have remained unchanged or the changes have been minimal, leading to a stable trend in order values over the years. Alternatively, there could be other factors that affect order values, such as the number of participants or the type of meal, which have remained consistent over the years, resulting in a stable trend.

4. Describe the variability that you observe in the plot and how that corresponds to the strength you calculated.

In the plot of “YYYY_Meal_Served_Year” and “Order_Value”, we can observe a lot of variability in the data. While the general trend appears to be a gradual increase in order value over the years, there are many fluctuations in the data around this trend. These fluctuations mean that the relationship between the variables is not very strong, despite being statistically significant.

The variability in the plot corresponds to the correlation coefficient of 0.007286711, which is a very weak positive correlation. This indicates that the two variables are almost independent of each other, and that the year in which a meal was served does not have much influence on the order value.The remaining variation is likely due to other factors, such as changes in the economy, consumer preferences, and competition.

We can conclude that while there is a small positive relationship between the two variables, it is not very strong, and there is a lot of variability in the data that cannot be explained by the year in which the meal was served.

PAIR II : One variable is Categorical and the other is Numeric

1. Create an appropriate plot to visualize the relationship between categorical “Type of Meals” and numeric variable “Meal Served each year”

# Remove outliers in Type _of_Meal and YYYY_Meal_Served_Year
smd_cleaned <- smd %>% 
  filter(YYYY_Meal_Served_Year != 2013 & YYYY_Meal_Served_Year != 2019) %>% 
  group_by(Type_of_Meal, YYYY_Meal_Served_Year) %>% 
  mutate(Order_Value = ifelse(Order_Value < quantile(Order_Value, 0.05) | Order_Value > quantile(Order_Value, 0.95), NA, Order_Value))

# Plot to visualize the relationship between categorical and numeric variables
ggplot(smd_cleaned, aes(x = factor(YYYY_Meal_Served_Year), fill = Type_of_Meal)) +
  geom_bar(position = "stack") +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Meals Sold", fill = "Type of Meal", title = "Type of Meals sold by year") +
  theme_minimal()+
   theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 18, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
        legend.position = "right", legend.justification = "center",
        panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        axis.line = element_line(linewidth = 1),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 10),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"))

2. Describe the form, direction, and strength of the observed relationship.

The form of the observed relationship between “Type_of_Meal” and “YYYY_Meal_Served_Year” is a stacked bar chart, which shows the proportion of each type of meal served in each year.

The direction of the relationship is positive. As the years increase, the number of meals served for each type of meal also increases.

Since “Type_of_Meal” is a categorical variable and “YYYY_Meal_Served_Year” is a numeric variable, we cannot calculate correlation coefficient as we did for two numeric variables.However, based on the stacked bar plot, the relationship between “Type_of_Meal” and “YYYY_Meal_Served_Year” appears to be weak and potentially non-existent. The stacked bar plot shows that the distribution of meal types is relatively consistent across years, with no clear pattern or trend.

3. Explain what this relationship means in the context of the data.

The relationship between “Type_of_Meal” and “YYYY_Meal_Served_Year” indicates how the distribution of meals served in different years varies by the type of meal. The stacked bar chart shows the proportion of each type of meal served for each year.

For example, we can see that the proportion of breakfast meals served has decreased over time, while the proportion of dinner meals served has increased. This could indicate a change in the preferences of the customers or a change in the restaurant’s focus.

Also, there has been a significant increase in the number of breakfast meals served in recent years compared to lunch and dinner meals. This suggests that there has been a shift in the dining preferences of customers towards breakfast over the years.

The chart also shows that there is a consistent trend in the proportion of lunch and dinner meals served, indicating that the restaurant has maintained its popularity for these meals over the years. This relationship helps us to understand how the restaurant’s menu and offerings have changed over time and can provide insights into the dining trends and customer preferences and trends.

4. Describe the variability that you observe in the plot and how that corresponds to the strength you calculated in #2 above.

As the plot shows, there is considerable variability in the number of meals served for each type of meal across the years. This variability corresponds to a relatively weak relationship between the two variables, as indicated by the low strength value calculated earlier.

The stacked bar chart also shows that there is no clear pattern or trend in the data over time, with some types of meals showing an increase in the number of meals served in some years and a decrease in others. Overall, while there appears to be some association between the two variables, the variability in the data suggests that other factors beyond year and meal type may be influencing the number of meals served.

1. Clean the data for any outlier/extreme values using the filtering technique and create an appropriate plot to visualize the distribution of this variable. (4 marks)

q1 <- quantile(Merged$MealPrice, 0.25)
q3 <- quantile(Merged$MealPrice, 0.75)
iqr_x <- IQR(Merged$MealPrice)

data1 <- Merged[(Merged$MealPrice >= q1 - 1.5*iqr_x) & (Merged$MealPrice <= q3 + 1.5*iqr_x), ]
ggplot(data1, aes(x = "", y = MealPrice)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill = "#f2c595", color = "black") +
  labs(x = "", y = "Meal Price", title = "Boxplot of Meal Prices")


2. Continued from #1, for any outliers present in the data. Specify the criteria used to identify them and provide a logical explanation for how you handled them. (4 marks)

I applied the interquartile range (IQR) method to find outliers in the data. Any data point outside the range (Q1 - 1.5IQR, Q3 + 1.5IQR) was regarded as an outlier. I calculated the IQR by subtracting the 25th percentile (Q1) from the 75th percentile (Q3).I made the decision to remove the outliers from the dataset after finding them. This is because outliers can skew analysis and reduce the precision of statistical models. Removing outliers can increase the analysis’s accuracy and generate more insightful results.

7. Choose and calculate a measure of spread (SD, MAD or IQR) that is appropriate for your chosen measure of central tendency. Explain why you chose this as your measure of spread. (2 marks)
I previously solved on the median as the indicator of central tendency because it is less responsive to outliers and extreme values than the mean. Therefore, it is important to use a spread measure that is resistant to outliers. A reliable measure of spread that is less vulnerable to outliers than the standard deviation is the interquartile range (IQR). I will therefore calculate my spread using the IQR.

The resulting boxplot will show the median, quartiles, and any outliers present in the data.

# Calculate IQR
q1 <- quantile(Merged$MealPrice, 0.25)
q3 <- quantile(Merged$MealPrice, 0.75)
iqr_x <- q3 - q1

# Create boxplot
ggplot(Merged, aes(x="", y=MealPrice)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill = "#abc9bd", color = "black") +
  labs(x = "", y = "Meal Price", title = "Boxplot of Meal Prices") +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(q1 - 1.5*iqr_x, q3 + 1.5*iqr_x))

library(readxl)
MergedOrders2 <- read_excel("Datasets/MergedOrders2.xlsx")
library(dplyr)
# Create bins for meal prices
bins <- seq(0, 450, by = 50)

# Bin the meal prices
MergedOrders2$MealPrice <- as.numeric(as.character(MergedOrders2$MealPrice))
bins <- seq(0, 450, by = 50)
MergedOrders2$price_range <- cut(MergedOrders2$MealPrice, bins, include.lowest = TRUE)


# Group by price range and calculate proportions
merged_prop <- MergedOrders2 %>%
  group_by(price_range) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(Proportion = count / sum(count))

# Create bar plot
ggplot(merged_prop, aes(x = price_range, y = Proportion, fill = price_range)) +
   scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 0.04)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "YlOrBr") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Price Range", y = "Proportion", title = "Distribution of Meal Prices (Proportions)")+
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"))

Transformations are typically not required on a uniform distribution of data, as it is already evenly distributed across the range of values. A uniform distribution has a constant probability density function (PDF) across the range of values, and any transformation applied to the data would not change this property.
